.TH DSESH 1 "June 2026" "dsesh 0.1.0" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
dsesh \- detachable terminal sessions with retained screen state
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B dsesh
.RI [ options ]
.B new
.RI socket
.B --
.RI command
.br
.B dsesh
.RI [ options ]
.B attach
.RI socket
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B dsesh
runs one command behind a Unix socket. Clients can detach and reattach while the
server keeps a vt100 screen model, so reattachment redraws the latest retained
terminal state before live output resumes.
.SH COMMANDS
.TP
.B new SOCKET -- COMMAND [ARGS...]
Start a new session and attach to it.
.TP
.B attach SOCKET
Attach to an existing session socket.
.TP
.B run SOCKET -- COMMAND [ARGS...]
Attach to SOCKET if it exists, otherwise create the session and attach. When
SOCKET already exists, COMMAND may be omitted.
.SH FLAKE APPS
.TP
.B nix run .#dr -- COMMAND [ARGS...]
Create
.B /tmp/.dsesh
and run COMMAND through
.B dsesh run
using a UUID-named socket under that directory.
.SH KEYS
.TP
.B Ctrl-\e
Detach the current client without stopping the child process.
.SH STATUS MESSAGES
.TP
.B [detached - SOCKET]
Printed with the session socket path when the current client detaches from a
live session.
.TP
.B [EOF - ended session]
Printed when the child process exits or is terminated and the session ends.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.B --cols N, --rows N
Initial PTY size used when the client terminal size cannot be detected.
